      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "57361805c733d932352d52fa868fb238e509cb45",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2016-11-14 22:08:45.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\n(1 comment)\n\nPatch is technically correct, but has exposed something strange.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "ed4f3bcc0ac9871c83c61dc4d21a774f44614ced",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 676,
        "name": "Steve Guminski",
        "email": "stephenx.guminski@intel.com",
        "username": "sguminsx",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2016-11-15 18:51:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI've come across other cases (over 60) where struct l_wait_info variables are getting initialized to zero.  The cases I've looked at so far are all the same usage as in this patch: waiting for a new kernel thread to indicate that it has started.  Replacing l_wait_event() with the native wait_event() seems like the right way to handle this.  Since the scope of this is quite large, should I create a new ticket to take a look at these initializers?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e7a38784ad20cc6c298f2126ecb5dc914f911dc4",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2016-11-15 22:08:56.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nYou are right, these cases are where the thread is waiting forever for the other thread to either start successfully or exit. That kind of change should be done in a separate patch.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "c4c20301510ec142033bf298a2cc4a58574b5d1c",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 676,
        "name": "Steve Guminski",
        "email": "stephenx.guminski@intel.com",
        "username": "sguminsx",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2016-11-16 13:54:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nI've written LU-8841 for the work needed to replace the zeroed lwi initializers.\n\nFor the current patch, do you want me to use LWI_TIMEOUT with zeroed parameters, or restore the original \"{ 0 }\"  initializer to make it easier to find for LU-8841?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
